Intuition
Since both arrays are sorted, we can use two pointers and compare elements one by one.

If both elements are equal → common element found.
If nums1[i] < nums2[j], move i because smaller values cannot match later.
Otherwise move j.
This avoids checking every pair and efficiently finds the first common element.

Approach
Initialize two pointers i = 0 and j = 0.
Traverse both arrays while pointers are inside bounds:
If nums1[i] == nums2[j], return that value.
If nums1[i] < nums2[j], increment i.
Else increment j.
If traversal ends without a match, return -1.
Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n+m)

Space complexity:
O(1)

Code
class Solution {
    public int getCommon(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {
        int i = 0, j = 0;

        while(i < nums1.length && j < nums2.length) {
            if(nums1[i] == nums2[j]) return nums1[i];

            if(nums1[i] < nums2[j]) i++;
            else j++;
        }

        return -1;
    }
}
method 2: : Hash Set Approach
Intuition
Instead of comparing elements one by one, we can store all elements of nums1 in an unordered_set for fast lookup.

Then traverse nums2 and check whether the current element exists in the set.

If found, return that element as the common value.

Approach
Create an unordered_set.
Insert all elements of nums1 into the set.
Traverse nums2:
If current element exists in the set, return it.
If no common element is found, return -1.
Complexity
Time complexity:O(n+m)

Space complexity:O(n)

class Solution {
    public int getCommon(int[] nums1, int[] nums2) {
        HashSet<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        for(int num : nums1)
            set.add(num);

        for(int num : nums2) {
            if(set.contains(num))
                return num;
        }

        return -1;
    }
}
